Predicting the World Cup Winner using Machine Learning¶

Millions of people across the world tune in to witness the FIFA World Cup, the most renowned and popular athletic event in the world. As the tournament draws near, excitement and expectation increase as fans, experts, and even casual observers speculate on the likely results and try to pick the final champion. There have been a lot of conversations, arguments, and predictions about who will win the World Cup based on a variety of variables, including team performance, player statistics, historical data, and even gut emotions.

This project's main aim is to investigate the possibilities of machine learning in the field of sports prediction, with a focus on the FIFA World Cup. By creating a strong prediction model, we intend to add to the body of knowledge and offer insightful information about the elements that affect the tournament's result.

Overall, this project aims to give a useful and cutting-edge method of forecasting the results of the tournament by fusing the thrill of the FIFA World Cup with the power of machine learning. By making a contribution to the field of sports analytics and prediction, we want to improve fan, stakeholder, and the larger sporting community comprehension of the game and produce insights.

wc_data =  pd.read_csv("international_results.csv") 
wc_data["date"] = pd.to_datetime(wc_data["date"])
wc_data = wc_data[(wc_data["date"] >= "2018-9-1")].reset_index(drop=True) # So after 2018 September

wc_rank = pd.read_csv("fifa_ranking.csv") #rankings
wc_rank["rank_date"] = pd.to_datetime(wc_rank["rank_date"]) 
wc_rank = wc_rank[(wc_rank["rank_date"] >= "2018-9-1")].reset_index(drop=True) # So after 2018 September

wc_rank["country_full"] = wc_rank["country_full"].str.replace("Korea Republic", "South Korea") # Change korea name
wc_rank["country_full"] = wc_rank["country_full"].str.replace("IR Iran", "Iran") # Change Iran name
wc_rank["country_full"] = wc_rank["country_full"].str.replace("USA", "United States") # Change USA name
wc_rank = wc_rank.set_index(['rank_date']).groupby(['country_full'], group_keys=False).resample('D').first().fillna(method='ffill').reset_index()

# Now merge everything
wc_final = wc_data.merge(wc_rank[["country_full", "total_points", "previous_points", "rank", "rank_change", "rank_date"]], left_on=["date", "home_team"], right_on=["rank_date", "country_full"]).drop(["rank_date", "country_full"], axis=1)
wc_final = wc_final.merge(wc_rank[["country_full", "total_points", "previous_points", "rank", "rank_change", "rank_date"]], left_on=["date", "away_team"], right_on=["rank_date", "country_full"], suffixes=("_home", "_away")).drop(["rank_date", "country_full"], axis=1)

We import our data from kaggle and we use two data set FIFA World Ranking and International football results.

So in the prepration we were only interested data from 2018 to 2022 so we did that and also needed to change some name because of the different name for same country in different dataset.

Data Collection¶

We gathered two data CSV files: "results.csv" (containing the game results between national teams) and "fifa_ranking.csv" (containing FIFA rankings). Then the game results data is stored in the df DataFrame, and the FIFA rankings data is stored in the rank DataFrame. We filtered the data to get data only after August 1, 2018, which corresponds to the start of the 2022 World Cup cycle.

Processing Data¶

The game results and rankings dataframes were then copied to new variables (df_wc and rank_wc) in order to prepare for combining them. The rank DataFrame and the df_wc DataFrame are merged twice to form the df_wc_ranked DataFrame. The "date" and "home_team" columns from df_wc as well as the "rank_date" and "country_full" columns from rank are used in the initial merging. It updates the df_wc_ranked DataFrame with the home team's ranking data. The "date" and "away_team" columns from df_wc_ranked (the outcome of the first merge) and the "rank_date" and "country_full" columns from rank are the foundation of the second merging. It updates the df_wc_ranked DataFrame with the away team's ranking data. Finally, the df_wc_ranked DataFrame has the extra columns "rank_date" and "country_full" removed.

The concept behind feature engineering is to identify potential factors that can significantly influence the prediction of football games. Based on intuition, we believe the following features could have an impact:

Previous game points earned Goals scored and conceded in previous matches The significance of the game (friendly or competitive) Team rankings Changes in team rankings over time Goals scored and conceded against teams with different rankings

def find_result(home, away):
    if home > away:
        return pd.Series([0, 3, 0])
    if home < away:
        return pd.Series([1, 0, 3])
    else:
        return pd.Series([2, 1, 1])

results = wc_final.apply(lambda x: find_result(x["home_score"], x["away_score"]), axis=1)

Next, we generate columns that will facilitate the creation of the features. These columns include the difference in rankings, points earned in the game compared to the rank of the opposing team, and the difference in goals scored during the game. It is important to create these features separately for both the home and away teams, ensuring that features other than differences are accounted for.

In [10]:
wc_final["rank_dif"] = wc_final["rank_home"] - wc_final["rank_away"]
wc_final["sg"] = wc_final["home_score"] - wc_final["away_score"]
wc_final["points_home_by_rank"] = wc_final["home_team_points"]/wc_final["rank_away"]
wc_final["points_away_by_rank"] = wc_final["away_team_points"]/wc_final["rank_home"]

Possibilities:

  • Average rank and average rank difference (test for full and test for 5 games, analyze the best)
  • Goals scored by ranking of the teams faced (and the difference)
  • Goals conceded by ranking of the teams faced (and the difference)

To create the features, I will divide the dataset into two separate parts: one for the home team and another for the away team. I will then combine these two datasets and calculate the values based on past games. Following this, I will once again separate and merge the datasets, thereby restoring the original dataset. This process enhances the efficiency of feature creation.

In [13]:
home_team = wc_final[["date", "home_team", "home_score", "away_score", "rank_home", "rank_away","rank_change_home", "total_points_home", "result", "rank_dif", "points_home_by_rank", "home_team_points"]]

away_team = wc_final[["date", "away_team", "away_score", "home_score", "rank_away", "rank_home","rank_change_away", "total_points_away", "result", "rank_dif", "points_away_by_rank", "away_team_points"]]

home_team.columns = [h.replace("home_", "").replace("_home", "").replace("away_", "suf_").replace("_away", "_suf") for h in home_team.columns]

away_team.columns = [a.replace("away_", "").replace("_away", "").replace("home_", "suf_").replace("_home", "_suf") for a in away_team.columns]

team_stats = home_team.append(away_team)

We now have a prepared database for creating predictive features. These features will include:

  1. Average number of goals scored by the team in the World Cup Cycle.
  2. Average number of goals scored by the team in the last five games.
  3. Average number of goals conceded by the team in the World Cup Cycle.
  4. Average number of goals conceded by the team in the last five games.
  5. Average FIFA rank of the teams faced by the team in the World Cup Cycle.
  6. Average FIFA rank of the teams faced by the team in the last five games.
  7. Total FIFA points earned during the cycle.
  8. Total FIFA points earned in the last five games.
  9. Average points earned per game in the World Cup Cycle.

stats_val = []

for index, row in team_stats.iterrows():
    team = row["team"]
    date = row["date"]
    past_games = team_stats.loc[(team_stats["team"] == team) & (team_stats["date"] < date)].sort_values(by=['date'], ascending=False)
    last_5 = past_games.head(5)
    
    goals = past_games["score"].mean()
    goals_l5 = last_5["score"].mean()
    
    goals_suf = past_games["suf_score"].mean()
    goals_suf_l5 = last_5["suf_score"].mean()
    
    rank = past_games["rank_suf"].mean()
    rank_l5 = last_5["rank_suf"].mean()
    
    if len(last_5) > 0:
        points = past_games["total_points"].values[0] - past_games["total_points"].values[-1]
        points_l5 = last_5["total_points"].values[0] - last_5["total_points"].values[-1] 
    else:
        points = 0
        points_l5 = 0
        
    gp = past_games["team_points"].mean()
    gp_l5 = last_5["team_points"].mean()
    
    gp_rank = past_games["points_by_rank"].mean()
    gp_rank_l5 = last_5["points_by_rank"].mean()
    
    stats_val.append([goals, goals_l5, goals_suf, goals_suf_l5, rank, rank_l5, points, points_l5, gp, gp_l5, gp_rank, gp_rank_l5])

def create_db(df):
    columns = ["home_team", "away_team", "target", "rank_dif", "home_goals_mean", "home_rank_mean", "away_goals_mean", "away_rank_mean", "home_rank_mean_l5", "away_rank_mean_l5", "home_goals_suf_mean", "away_goals_suf_mean", "home_goals_mean_l5", "away_goals_mean_l5", "home_goals_suf_mean_l5", "away_goals_suf_mean_l5", "home_game_points_rank_mean", "home_game_points_rank_mean_l5", "away_game_points_rank_mean", "away_game_points_rank_mean_l5","is_friendly_0", "is_friendly_1"]

    base = df.loc[:, columns]
    base.loc[:, "goals_dif"] = base["home_goals_mean"] - base["away_goals_mean"]
    base.loc[:, "goals_dif_l5"] = base["home_goals_mean_l5"] - base["away_goals_mean_l5"]
    base.loc[:, "goals_suf_dif"] = base["home_goals_suf_mean"] - base["away_goals_suf_mean"]
    base.loc[:, "goals_suf_dif_l5"] = base["home_goals_suf_mean_l5"] - base["away_goals_suf_mean_l5"]
    base.loc[:, "goals_per_ranking_dif"] = (base["home_goals_mean"] / base["home_rank_mean"]) - (base["away_goals_mean"] / base["away_rank_mean"])
    base.loc[:, "dif_rank_agst"] = base["home_rank_mean"] - base["away_rank_mean"]
    base.loc[:, "dif_rank_agst_l5"] = base["home_rank_mean_l5"] - base["away_rank_mean_l5"]
    base.loc[:, "dif_points_rank"] = base["home_game_points_rank_mean"] - base["away_game_points_rank_mean"]
    base.loc[:, "dif_points_rank_l5"] = base["home_game_points_rank_mean_l5"] - base["away_game_points_rank_mean_l5"]

    model_df = base[["home_team", "away_team", "target", "rank_dif", "goals_dif", "goals_dif_l5", "goals_suf_dif", "goals_suf_dif_l5", "goals_per_ranking_dif", "dif_rank_agst", "dif_rank_agst_l5", "dif_points_rank", "dif_points_rank_l5", "is_friendly_0", "is_friendly_1"]]
    return model_df

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, roc_curve, roc_auc_score


def analyze(model):
    # Set custom colors for the graphs
    color_test = 'blue'
    color_train = 'green'


    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])  # test AUC
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color=color_test, label="test")


    fpr_train, tpr_train, _ = roc_curve(y_train, model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1])  # train AUC
    plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, color=color_train, label="train")
    auc_test = roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
    
    auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1])
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('AUC score is %.2f on test and %.2f on training' % (auc_test, auc_train))
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.bar(['Test AUC', 'Train AUC'], [auc_test, auc_train], color=[color_test, color_train])
    plt.title('AUC Comparison')
    plt.xlabel('Dataset')
    plt.ylabel('AUC Score')
    plt.show()
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(9, 7))
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, model.predict(X_test))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="BuGn_r")
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show()

ROC Curve and AUC Score:¶

For the predictions made by the model on the test and training datasets, the function determines the ROC curve and AUC (Area Under the Curve) score. It computes the false positive rate (FPR) and true positive rate (TPR) for various probability thresholds using the roc_curve function from sklearn.metrics. The ROC curve is produced by using plt.plot to plot the FPR and TPR data. The curve displays how well the model is able to differentiate between positive and negative samples. The roc_auc_score function from sklearn.metrics is used to determine the AUC scores for the test and training datasets. The generated test and training curves' custom colors are used to illustrate the ROC curve and AUC values. For reference, our figure has a diagonal dotted line (k--) that represents a random classifier.

Confusion Matrix Visualization:¶

The confusion matrix for the model's predictions on the test dataset is calculated using the function. The confusion_matrix function from sklearn.metrics is used to generate the confusion matrix. The true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative values are shown on the resultant confusion matrix using sns.heatmap. With annot=True, the heatmap is annotated with the actual values, and fmt="d" formats the numbers as integers. The plot of the confusion matrix is shown. The analyze function generates ROC curve visualizations, computes AUC scores, and displays the confusion matrix to aid in assessing the effectiveness of a machine learning model. These assessment measures shed light on the model's classification and prediction capabilities.

Reason for model selection¶

Although the Random Forest model performs marginally better, it appears to be overfit. Gradient Boosting's AUC-ROC analysis reveals a model with nearly the same performance but a smaller risk of overfitting, which is why it was chosen.

The find_stats function takes a team name as input and retrieves statistical information about that team from a dataframe base_df. Here's a breakdown of the statistics calculated in the function:

past_games: Selects all the rows in base_df where the "team" column matches team_1 and sorts them by date. last5: Selects the last 5 rows in base_df where the "team" column matches team_1 and sorts them by date. The calculated statistics are:

team_1_rank: The rank of team_1 in the latest game.
team_1_goals: The average number of goals scored by team_1 in all past games.
team_1_goals_l5: The average number of goals scored by team_1 in the last 5 games.
team_1_goals_suf: The average number of goals conceded by team_1 in all past games.
team_1_goals_suf_l5: The average number of goals conceded by team_1 in the last 5 games.
team_1_rank_suf: The average rank of the opponents faced by team_1 in all past games.
team_1_rank_suf_l5: The average rank of the opponents faced by team_1 in the last 5 games.
team_1_gp_rank: The average number of points earned by team_1 based on the rank of the opponents faced in all past games.
team_1_gp_rank_l5: The average number of points earned by team_1 based on the rank of the opponents faced in the last 5 games.
The function then returns a list containing these calculated statistics for team_1.

def find_stats(team_1):
#team_1 = "Qatar"
    past_games = base_df[(base_df["team"] == team_1)].sort_values("date")
    last5 = base_df[(base_df["team"] == team_1)].sort_values("date").tail(5)

    team_1_rank = past_games["rank"].values[-1]
    team_1_goals = past_games.score.mean()
    team_1_goals_l5 = last5.score.mean()
    team_1_goals_suf = past_games.suf_score.mean()
    team_1_goals_suf_l5 = last5.suf_score.mean()
    team_1_rank_suf = past_games.rank_suf.mean()
    team_1_rank_suf_l5 = last5.rank_suf.mean()
    team_1_gp_rank = past_games.points_by_rank.mean()
    team_1_gp_rank_l5 = last5.points_by_rank.mean()

    return [team_1_rank, team_1_goals, team_1_goals_l5, team_1_goals_suf, team_1_goals_suf_l5, team_1_rank_suf, team_1_rank_suf_l5, team_1_gp_rank, team_1_gp_rank_l5]

def find_features(team_1, team_2):
    rank_dif = team_1[0] - team_2[0]
    goals_dif = team_1[1] - team_2[1]
    goals_dif_l5 = team_1[2] - team_2[2]
    goals_suf_dif = team_1[3] - team_2[3]
    goals_suf_dif_l5 = team_1[4] - team_2[4]
    goals_per_ranking_dif = (team_1[1]/team_1[5]) - (team_2[1]/team_2[5])
    dif_rank_agst = team_1[5] - team_2[5]
    dif_rank_agst_l5 = team_1[6] - team_2[6]
    dif_gp_rank = team_1[7] - team_2[7]
    dif_gp_rank_l5 = team_1[8] - team_2[8]
    
    return [rank_dif, goals_dif, goals_dif_l5, goals_suf_dif, goals_suf_dif_l5, goals_per_ranking_dif, dif_rank_agst, dif_rank_agst_l5, dif_gp_rank, dif_gp_rank_l5, 1, 0]

                    control.append((advanced*2)[a][1])

                    control.append((advanced*2)[a][1])
                else:
                    control.append((advanced*2)[a][0])

        playoffs[p] = [[control[c], control[c+1]] for c in range(0, len(control)-1, 1) if c%2 == 0]

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, the goal of this study was to use a machine learning model to forecast which teams will advance from the group stage of the 2022 FIFA World Cup. To train a gradient boosting classifier, we used team statistics and historical match data. Probabilities of each team's success in forthcoming games were provided by the model. We identified the teams that advanced from each group by recreating the group stage matches and using the predictions from the model. The amount of points earned depending on the outcomes of the games was one of the criteria for moving on, with goal differentials and tiebreakers also being taken into account. As a result, every time we had a champion, it was different, and England came in last with about 40% accuracy. It is crucial to remember that the performance of the machine learning model and the quality of the historical data have a major role in how accurate the forecasts are. Additionally, there are a number of variables that might affect the results of the games, including injuries, team dynamics, and unforeseen circumstances.

Future Work¶

For future work we could incorporate additional features, such as player-level data and team formations that can potentially impact positively to our prediction. Also we can explore different machine learning algorithms to enhance prediction accuracy. Additionally, real-time data updates during the tournament would enhance the structure and complexity of the dataset and potentially provide a solid ground to the data. However, this can be fairly difficult to implement.
